{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:22:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2382"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2382"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.61,0.05,0.16,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103611"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2382"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2382"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86028"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"},{"type":"tags","id":"1453"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15077"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42480"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103611"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a general health review after presenting with elevated blood pressure during his previous two visits in the past six months. He was initially advised on controlling his hypertension with weight loss and diet modification before starting medical therapy, but he has since been unable to lose any weight. Since then, he was started on a calcium channel blocker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. His current medications are amlodipine 5 mg daily and simvastatin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 155/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. His BMI is 33 kg/m\u00b2 (31 kg/m\u00b2 in the previous visit). His blood pressure from his previous two visits was 148/86 mmHg (six months ago) and 149/90 mmHg (three months ago).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood laboratory results show raised triglycerides 3.0 mmol/L (0.5-1.7) and raised LDL cholesterol 3.0 mmol/L (\u0026lt;2.6).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for this patient\u0027s hypertension?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Education on weight loss management","Add perindopril 5 mg daily","Change amlodipine 5 mg to perindopril 5 mg","Increase amlodipine to 10 mg daily","Add perindopril 5 mg and losartan 50 mg"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has poorly controlled hypertension, with elevated blood pressure readings across six months despite the promotion of optimal lifestyle habits and blood pressure-lowering drug therapy. In general, a target blood pressure of \u0026lt;140/90 mmHg is recommended for patients with uncomplicated hypertension as per the current Australian guidelines for hypertension management (2016).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient was started on a moderate dose of amlodipine, a calcium channel blocker. If blood pressure target is not reached within three months, a second anti-hypertensive drug from a different pharmacological class at a low-moderate dose should be initiated (rather than increasing the dose of the first drug).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd perindopril 5 mg daily\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. A combination of anti-hypertensive therapy should be initiated since his blood pressure is poorly controlled despite being on amlodipine. An effective combination of calcium-channel blocker and an ACE-inhibitor is particularly useful in the presence of diabetes and/or lipid abnormalities. Perindopril could be added to his medication regimen and can be administered as a single combination tablet to reduce tablet burden.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEducation on weight loss management\u003C/strong\u003E should still be recommended at every visit. However, there is higher mortality benefit in prescribing a combination anti-hypertensive drug therapy at this particular visit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange amlodipine 5 mg to perindopril 5 mg\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it would involve discontinuing a medication that may be providing some benefit. It\u0027s generally better to add a second agent from a different class rather than switching medications entirely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease amlodipine to 10 mg daily\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best approach. When blood pressure target is not reached within three months, adding a second anti-hypertensive drug from a different pharmacological class at a low-moderate dose is preferred over increasing the dose of the first drug.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd perindopril 5 mg and losartan 50 mg\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. It\u0027s important to note that a combination of ACE inhibitors and angiotensin-receptor blockers should be avoided, as it increases the risk of renal dysfunction without providing additional benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECombining calcium-channel blockers with angiotensin receptor blockers or thiazide diuretics are also examples of effective anti-hypertensive therapy. The key to management is recognizing when monotherapy is insufficient and appropriately adding a second agent from a different class to achieve better blood pressure control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A calcium-channel blocker combined with an ACE-inhibitor can be an effective approach to the management of hypertension when a single agent fails to work.","If blood pressure target is not reached within three months, a second anti-hypertensive drug from a different pharmacological class at a low-moderate dose should be initiated rather than increasing the dose of the first drug."],"references":["Whelton PK, Carey RM, Aronow WS, et al. 2017 ACC/AHA/AAPA/ABC/ACPM/AGS/APhA/ASH/ASPC/NMA/PCNA Guideline for the Prevention, Detection, Evaluation, and Management of High Blood Pressure in Adults: A Report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on Clinical Practice Guidelines. Hypertension 2018; 71:e13.","Williams B, Mancia G, Spiering W, et al. 2018 ESC/ESH Guidelines for the management of arterial hypertension. Eur Heart J 2018; 39:3021.","Hypertension in adults: Diagnosis and management. National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE). http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ng136","National Vascular Disease Prevention Alliance. Australian Absolute Cardiovascular Disease Risk Calculator[Internet]. Melbourne: NVDPA; [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://www.cvdcheck.org.au/calculator","National Heart Foundation of Australia. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults \u2013 2016 [Internet]. Melbourne: National Heart Foundation of Australia; 2016 [cited 2025 May 23]. Available from: https://assets.contentstack.io/v3/assets/blt8a393bb3b76c0ede/bltbf3d36e10b48f01f/65b0963ea933e532ae0286de/01_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf","Atkins ER, Perkovic V. Blood pressure: at what level is treatment worthwhile?. Aust Prescr 2019;42:127-30. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2019.038"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86028"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2382"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86028"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T20:13:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-24T20:13:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2382"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103611"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66